  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an
assertion failure inside CallBase::paramHasNonNullAttr, which requires the
queried argument to be a pointer-typed operand. In the provided IR, a call
is made with a <2 x ptr> argument (vector of pointers). SimplifyCFG's
passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined calls paramHasNonNullAttr on the argument
operand without ensuring it is a pointer type, thus violating the
precondition when the operand is a vector of pointers.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nThe stack trace shows the failure at CallBase::paramHasNonNullAttr,
invoked from passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined (SimplifyCFG.cpp:8226/8227). The
reproducer demonstrates a vector GEP producing a <2 x ptr> that is passed to
a function. SimplifyCFG tries to reason about undefined behavior when
passing null to a nonnull+noundef argument. However, the code assumes
pointer type and doesn't guard for vector types, leading to the
assertion.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nWithin passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined,
the code does:\n  if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(C) &&
CB->paramHasNonNullAttr(ArgIdx, false))\nThis assumes the argument is a
pointer operand. When the operand is a vector of pointers,
getArgOperand(ArgNo)->getType()->isPointerTy() is false, triggering the
assert in paramHasNonNullAttr. The logic should only apply this
pointer-specific check when the argument operand is actually a pointer.
Currently there is no type guard.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nAdd a type
check before calling paramHasNonNullAttr to ensure the argument operand is
pointer-typed. If it is not a pointer (e.g., vector of pointers), skip the
pointer-specific nonnull handling path. Specifically, change:\n  if
(isa<ConstantPointerNull>(C) &&\n      CB->paramHasNonNullAttr(ArgIdx,
/*AllowUndefOrPoison=*/false))\n    return !PtrValueMayBeModified;\ninto:\n
if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(C)) {\n    Type *ArgTy =
